WEBVTT

00:00:15.687 --> 00:00:17.520
TINA SRIVASTRAVA: So
now we're going to dive

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:19.320
into the flight environment.

00:00:26.770 --> 00:00:28.060
All right.

00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:31.923
So the first part is flying.

00:00:31.923 --> 00:00:33.340
Actually, let me
just pause there.

00:00:33.340 --> 00:00:36.382
Were there any other
questions about the charts

00:00:36.382 --> 00:00:37.090
and the airspace?

00:00:41.030 --> 00:00:41.690
OK, good.

00:00:41.690 --> 00:00:43.790
They're kind of related
to the flight environment,

00:00:43.790 --> 00:00:46.400
so feel free to jump in here.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:48.250
All right.

00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:51.150
So flying.

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:54.000
So there's a fair amount
of work that a pilot

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.210
is supposed to do-- is actually
required to do before they fly.

00:00:58.210 --> 00:01:01.290
So you're supposed to become
familiar with information

00:01:01.290 --> 00:01:03.090
that pertains to your flight.

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:04.800
In fact, it's a very
good idea to do so,

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:07.860
that's exactly how you
become a safe pilot.

00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:10.950
So it's important to
understand information

00:01:10.950 --> 00:01:12.270
related to your flight.

00:01:12.270 --> 00:01:16.800
So there's not only the airport
that you're taking off from--

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:19.110
and when Phillip talks
about performance,

00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:21.720
he'll talk about the length
of runway that's required,

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:24.630
but you also want to know
about alternate airports

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:25.500
along your route.

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:28.380
So if I'm flying
from here to Maine,

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:32.310
for example, there's a lot
of airports along the route,

00:01:32.310 --> 00:01:35.280
I'd want to identify a
couple along the way,

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:39.000
understand what the weather
forecast is for those airports,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.880
whether or not they have
fuel, those types of things

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:43.980
are very relevant to know.

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:47.042
You're also supposed to
understand how much-- so we

00:01:47.042 --> 00:01:49.500
talked about-- so when you talk
about aircraft performance,

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:53.640
you'll understand what length
of runway you require in order

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:56.040
to land, and then
you want to make sure

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:58.020
that the airports
that you've identified

00:01:58.020 --> 00:01:59.730
as alternate airports
along the way

00:01:59.730 --> 00:02:04.440
have long enough
runways for you to land.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:07.940
So let's talk about
some of the paperwork.

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:11.060
So there's this
acronym, ARROW, that's

00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:13.700
supposed to help you
remember the types of things

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:16.190
that you're required to
have inside the airplane.

00:02:16.190 --> 00:02:19.918
So there's an Airworthiness
Certificate, Registration.

00:02:19.918 --> 00:02:21.710
If you're going on an
international flight,

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:23.175
you need a radio license.

00:02:23.175 --> 00:02:24.550
It's actually
pretty easy to get.

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:26.870
So if you wanted to fly
from here to Canada,

00:02:26.870 --> 00:02:29.870
you only have to pay $60
to get your radio license

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:32.450
and you can go fly to
Canada, so it's great.

00:02:32.450 --> 00:02:35.750
And also the international
language of aviation

00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:36.410
is English.

00:02:36.410 --> 00:02:39.350
So even if you go to Montreal,
you don't have to learn French,

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:43.160
you can speak in English and
land there, so it's great.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:45.300
So O is the Operating
Limitations,

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:47.650
those are displayed
in various ways,

00:02:47.650 --> 00:02:50.557
such as your flight
manual and placards,

00:02:50.557 --> 00:02:52.390
and we'll give you some
pictures of placards

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:53.700
so you see what those are.

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:55.380
And then Weight and
Balance information,

00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:58.590
and we have a whole talk
just about calculating weight

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:02.730
and balance I think tomorrow.

00:03:02.730 --> 00:03:04.650
So operating limitations.

00:03:04.650 --> 00:03:07.740
So these are real restrictions
on the aircraft in terms

00:03:07.740 --> 00:03:10.830
of what is the
maximum speed you can

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:14.010
fly with and without
your flaps extended,

00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:16.360
and which kind of
procedures can you do.

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:18.330
And we talked about
certain aircraft

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:20.820
that you're allowed to do these
fancy aerobatic procedures

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:23.190
in and other aircraft where
that's not a good idea,

00:03:23.190 --> 00:03:26.550
because if you really push
your aircraft to enter a spin,

00:03:26.550 --> 00:03:30.430
it may be very difficult
to recover from it.

00:03:30.430 --> 00:03:32.090
And so there are
different things--

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:36.700
so one is called the POH or
the Pilot's Operating Handbook,

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:39.070
and I have a POH over
here, and it has a lot

00:03:39.070 --> 00:03:40.390
of great information in it.

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:42.182
So pretty much everything
Philip taught you

00:03:42.182 --> 00:03:45.100
about aircraft systems as
is in this book as well.

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:46.660
It tells you about--

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:51.040
everything about your airplane's
systems, its requirements,

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:54.250
its restrictions, and how you
calculate that runway length

00:03:54.250 --> 00:03:56.710
that you need to land and
your weight and balance,

00:03:56.710 --> 00:04:00.470
all that information
is inside these books.

00:04:00.470 --> 00:04:03.100
So this is an example of
some of those limitations

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:05.620
for an SR20 as an example--

00:04:05.620 --> 00:04:07.420
we were talking about
Cirrus aircraft.

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:09.580
And so you can see, the
same types of numbers

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:13.015
that Philip was pointing out
before, the different V speeds.

00:04:16.120 --> 00:04:19.510
And he had also talked about
these maneuverability limits

00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:21.440
as well.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:24.040
Minimum flight crew for a
lot of these small airplanes

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:27.580
is usually one, but some of
the very big, complex airplanes

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:30.820
and jet aircraft require
the co-pilot as well,

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:36.590
and some airplanes even require
another crew member as well.

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:39.370
So there are certain
aircraft instruments

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:41.410
that you require when you fly.

00:04:41.410 --> 00:04:44.870
So they're called
equipment requirements.

00:04:44.870 --> 00:04:48.640
So a VFR day, which is
Visual Flight Rules-- so

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:52.000
a nice sunny day, no
clouds, so you'll be doing

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.690
VFR your entire time getting
your private pilot's license

00:04:55.690 --> 00:04:58.410
except if you do a couple
days of instrument training,

00:04:58.410 --> 00:05:00.460
but the vast majority
of time, you're

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:03.040
talking about a VFR flight.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:06.940
So what do you need, you need
some of those key instruments

00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:09.160
we were just talking about--
your airspeed indicator,

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:13.270
your altimeter, a compass,
and then a couple of things

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:14.250
related to the engine.

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:16.810
So you understand about
the engine, its oil

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:19.220
pressure, temperature,
and you need

00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:21.183
to know things about your fuel.

00:05:21.183 --> 00:05:22.600
And a lot of them
have alternates,

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:24.820
you could measure your
fuel from different ways,

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:26.620
but somehow you must
have a fuel gauge

00:05:26.620 --> 00:05:27.970
to know how much fuel you have.

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:33.440
You also need to have
anti-collision strobe

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:37.550
lights that kind go
off, and seat belts.

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:39.470
Who knows what an ELT is?

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:43.803
Yes?

00:05:43.803 --> 00:05:45.470
AUDIENCE: Emergency
locator transmitter?

00:05:45.470 --> 00:05:46.762
TINA SRIVASTRAVA: That's right.

00:05:46.762 --> 00:05:51.860
And so that-- it's an emergency
device that basically activates

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:54.650
when your aircraft-- if
your aircraft is under

00:05:54.650 --> 00:05:56.930
duress and is
descending very rapidly,

00:05:56.930 --> 00:06:00.260
it goes off and emits
your location out so

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:04.525
that people can come and find
your aircraft very quickly.

00:06:04.525 --> 00:06:07.150
There are also some-- and these
numbers, by the way at the top,

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:09.550
in case it wasn't
clear, are regulations.

00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:10.840
So they're FAA regulations.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:16.720
So 91.105 is a regulation about
pilots sitting in their seat

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:18.190
when you're flying the airplane.

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:21.220
So for all practical purposes,
when you guys were flying,

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:25.180
you have to sit down and be
the pilot and fly the airplane.

00:06:25.180 --> 00:06:26.870
This isn't like a
big commercial jet

00:06:26.870 --> 00:06:28.828
we're going to get up
and start walking around,

00:06:28.828 --> 00:06:30.760
so you need you need
to basically sit down.

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:35.740
Seat belts.

00:06:35.740 --> 00:06:37.780
As a pilot in
command, you also get

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:39.460
to make the rules
for your flight.

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:42.160
So if you think you have some
kind of rowdy passengers,

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:45.090
you just tell them the rule
is you must wear your seat

00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:47.960
belt at all times.

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:52.247
The actuality is that there are
certain times and restrictions

00:06:52.247 --> 00:06:53.080
where it's required.

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:55.360
So taxi, takeoff,
landing is required

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:58.330
to wear your seat belt, but you
can extend that rule and say,

00:06:58.330 --> 00:07:02.610
at all times you must
always wear your seat belt.

00:07:02.610 --> 00:07:04.590
There's also an
interesting regulation

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:08.010
that says that passengers
can't interfere with the crew

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:09.862
members, but I will
point out that depending

00:07:09.862 --> 00:07:11.820
on who your passengers
are, they may or may not

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:15.830
comply with that regulation.

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:18.920
We already talked about the
different altimeter settings.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:22.160
So kind of-- it can be the
case that you-- instead

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.910
of being the perfect
condition of 29.92,

00:07:25.910 --> 00:07:27.620
it might be the
case that you need

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:31.430
to adjust your altimeter
to that local setting.

00:07:31.430 --> 00:07:34.160
So we talked about
ADS where you can

00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:36.350
dial in the frequency
of the ADS and it

00:07:36.350 --> 00:07:38.360
announces the
weather information

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:39.800
for a particular area.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:42.530
They will provide
the setting that you

00:07:42.530 --> 00:07:44.990
need to set in that window.

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:51.350
So they'll say 29.98 or whatever
is the altimeter setting.

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:53.690
Also, if you're flying
over a bunch of places

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:55.520
and you're talking to
air traffic control,

00:07:55.520 --> 00:07:58.040
they will update you-- if they
hand you from one air traffic

00:07:58.040 --> 00:08:00.110
controller to another
air traffic controller,

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:01.610
one of the first
things they'll tell

00:08:01.610 --> 00:08:04.460
you is what is the altimeter
setting for that area

00:08:04.460 --> 00:08:06.860
so that everybody is
adjusted and everybody

00:08:06.860 --> 00:08:09.930
knows what altitude they're at.

00:08:09.930 --> 00:08:12.930
So there's a little
knob on your dial,

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:15.690
and you turn it until
that window on the right

00:08:15.690 --> 00:08:17.740
says the right number.

00:08:17.740 --> 00:08:19.650
Now if that's not
available, you already

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:22.620
have some information, which
is the airport elevation.

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:25.380
So also on those things
being passed around,

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:28.120
for a given airport, it tells
you what the elevation is.

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:31.770
So for example, if you know
that the airport is at 100 feet

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:33.630
elevation, you can
just-- and you're

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:37.200
sitting on the ground in your
aircraft getting your airplane

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.330
set up before you take
off, then you know

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:41.820
that you're at that 100 feet.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:45.960
So you can just keep turning
the dial until it says 100 feet,

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:49.980
and then that'll actually give
you the setting in the window.

00:08:54.740 --> 00:08:56.825
There's some restriction--
yes, go ahead.

00:08:56.825 --> 00:08:58.940
AUDIENCE: What if you're flying
into an uncontrolled airport

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:00.440
or you don't have
altimeter setting?

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:02.450
How do you [INAUDIBLE]?

00:09:02.450 --> 00:09:04.320
TINA SRIVASTRAVA: So
that happens a lot.

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:08.630
So you can basically look
at the nearest airport

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:09.885
is probably the best way.

00:09:09.885 --> 00:09:11.510
And those are the
times that you really

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:13.635
want to keep in mind what
Philip was talking about,

00:09:13.635 --> 00:09:17.570
that if you are going from
a hot place to a cold place,

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:20.150
you want to keep in mind
that hey, I might actually

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:23.370
be descending even though
my altimeter says I'm not.

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:27.140
But in general, if you have a
local setting that's nearby,

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:28.250
you're pretty much good.

00:09:28.250 --> 00:09:30.543
They don't vary dramatically
unless the weather's

00:09:30.543 --> 00:09:32.210
changing a lot, in
which case you really

00:09:32.210 --> 00:09:33.290
shouldn't be flying
because it means

00:09:33.290 --> 00:09:34.582
there's a huge front coming in.

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:39.520
So here's an airport diagram.

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:43.000
A lot of information here,
but one thing-- so this

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.400
is actually Bedford.

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:47.170
And so you can see
a couple of things

00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:49.570
you wouldn't see at other
places, such as the US Air

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:51.455
Force ramp.

00:09:51.455 --> 00:09:53.080
That's not going to
be at other places.

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:56.440
But you basically see these
two intersecting black lines.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:58.580
So those are the main runways.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:01.120
And each runway
is bi-directional.

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:02.650
So on one side--

00:10:02.650 --> 00:10:05.710
so it says-- the number's
very small right here next

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:06.360
to the mouse.

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:07.480
So 11.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:08.860
So that's runway 11.

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:10.810
And then on the other
side it says 29.

00:10:10.810 --> 00:10:13.900
So basically you land in one
direction, it's one number;

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:16.610
if you land in the other
direction, it's another number,

00:10:16.610 --> 00:10:20.380
and that number is corresponding
to the heading of that runway.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.270
And then you see a bunch
of lighter gray lines.

00:10:23.270 --> 00:10:25.960
So those are the
different taxiways.

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:28.117
And there's all
kinds of stuff here.

00:10:28.117 --> 00:10:29.950
I won't go through
everything, but one thing

00:10:29.950 --> 00:10:35.000
that's really relevant
is this acronym here.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.310
And it kind of
looks like a lasso.

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:41.270
What it's saying is,
the land and hold short.

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:43.410
So if you're given
an instruction-- so

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:45.900
when you have two
intersecting runways,

00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:48.260
they might want to
keep up the efficiency.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:50.420
They might want to have
you land while they

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:54.950
have another airplane taking
off on the other runway.

00:10:54.950 --> 00:10:58.290
And so there is a line that
says that if you given a land

00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:00.290
and hold short instruction,
that you're supposed

00:11:00.290 --> 00:11:02.120
to land-- that you're
supposed to hold short,

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:03.995
you're not supposed to
cross the intersecting

00:11:03.995 --> 00:11:07.250
runway because there's
traffic on that runway.

00:11:07.250 --> 00:11:07.750
Thanks.

